      <h3>Key OBS Tips</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Always use CBR (Constant Bitrate)</strong> — VBR causes buffering for viewers on slower connections. Twitch recommends CBR.</li>
        <li><strong>Use GPU encoding (NVENC/AMF)</strong> if your GPU supports it. It produces better quality than x264 at the same bitrate with minimal performance impact (2-5% FPS loss vs 15-30% for x264).</li>
        <li><strong>Twitch caps bitrate at 6,000 kbps</strong> for non-partners. YouTube allows much higher bitrates. If you're on Twitch, don't exceed 6,000 — it won't improve quality and will cause buffering.</li>
        <li><strong>Set keyframe interval to 2 seconds</strong> — both Twitch and YouTube require this. A different value causes encoding errors.</li>
        <li><strong>Add audio filters to your mic</strong> in OBS: Noise Suppression (RNNoise), Noise Gate, Compressor, and Limiter — in that order. This chain eliminates background noise, evens out your volume, and prevents clipping.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Internet Speed Requirements</h2>
      <p>Your upload speed determines the maximum stream quality you can push. Always use a wired ethernet connection — Wi-Fi packet loss causes stream stuttering regardless of speed.</p>
      <div class="table-wrapper">
        <table class="sortable-table">
          <thead>
